<br>
Obviously, if you weren't playing EQ, you could also be out there volunteering, climbing mountains, and building deep relationships with your loved ones.<br>
<br>
EQ has caused all kinds of problems with lots of relationships around me. And my wife and I have had lots of fights too.<br>
<br>
Although she doesn't like it when I sit for hours entranced by the computer screen, that's not necessarily the problem - it's that the game doesn't have a pause button.<br>
<br>
Joining a group or going on a raid is a commitment. Real humans around the world are depending on you to be in front of your computer screen and playing your part for the team. You can't just get up and walk away from your computer to help out around the home - virtual people die, and real people hate you.<br>
<br>
So, a lot of the frustration comes from the fact that any time my wife wants talk with me, needs my help with something urgent, my response was either &quot;just a minute&quot;, or &quot;I can't, I'll die&quot;. In the beginning it causes mild frustration in the people around you, but it can eventually become outrage.<br>
<br>
Because they aren't playing the game with you, they can't tell the difference between when you're in non-commitment mode (noodling around Freeport working on tradeskills) and mega-commitment mode (breaking into Fear). They associate bad feelings with the game, and then relationships deteriorate.<br>
<br>
So, I present EQ to my wife like I'm part of a Soccer League. I'm dealing with real human beings and they're counting on me to be there, but at the same time, it would be insane for me to be at Soccer practice, or playing games 60 hours a week. EQ is convenient and easy on the knees, so the potential is there to play a LOT.<br>
<br>
My wife and I have an uneasy truce now regarding EQ, but relations are improving. My guild does a big raid once a week, and during that time I'm completely free to dedicate myself to the game - the outside world can't reach me, and I feel I'm spending quality time playing the game. The rest of the time, I make sure I don't get into any situations I can't back out of quickly. The people I normally group with know I may have to step away from the computer mid-fight to deal with a real life situation. (/g afk, changing a diaper, don't let me die). The raid leader asks if I'm holding the baby before making me Secondary Assist (/gu slow talking holding baby...)<br>
<br>
If there's something unique raid going on, like helping a guildy take down Phinny, I let my wife know the situation and the amount of commitment and time required. She just appreciates being kept in the loop.<br>
<br>
In my opinion, playing 60 hours a week isn't healthy, no matter how you justify it. Ask yourself that question, when you're on your deathbed, looking back at your life, will you wish you got more levels or spent time living life?<br>
